com.stormpath.spring.security.provider

Class DefaultGroupGrantedAuthorityResolver

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.stormpath.spring.security.provider.DefaultGroupGrantedAuthorityResolver
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    GroupGrantedAuthorityResolver

    public class DefaultGroupGrantedAuthorityResolver
extends Object
implements GroupGrantedAuthorityResolver
    Default implementation of the GroupGrantedAuthorityResolver interface that allows a Stormpath Group to be translated into Spring Security granted authorities based on custom preferences.

    Overview

    This implementation converts a Group into one or more granted authorities based on one or more configured Modes:
    Mode (case insensitive) Behavior Example
    HREF Returns the Group's fully qualified HREF as the granted authority https://api.stormpath.com/v1/groups/upXiExAmPlEfA5L1G5ZaSQ
    ID Returns Group's globally unique identifier as the granted authority upXiExAmPlEfA5L1G5ZaSQ
    NAME Returns Group's name as the granted authority administrators

    Usage

    You can choose one or more modes either by referencing the Mode enum values directly, or by using the mode string names.

    For example, in code: 

     Set<DefaultGroupGrantedAuthorityResolver.Mode> modes = Collections.toSet(
     DefaultGroupGrantedAuthorityResolver.Mode.HREF, DefaultGroupGrantedAuthorityResolver.Mode.ID
 );
 groupRoleResolver.setModes(modes);

    Or maybe in spring.xml: 

     
      
          
              href
              id
    In the above configuration, each Group translates into two granted authorities: one is the raw href itself, the other one is the Group ID. You can specify one or more modes to translate into one or more granted authorities names respectively. modeNames are case-insensitive.

    WARNING: Group Names, while easier to read in code, can change at any time via a REST API call or by using the Stormpath UI Console. It is strongly recommended to use only the HREF or ID modes as these values will never change. Acquiring group names might also incur a REST server call, whereas the the HREF is guaranteed to be present.

        public Set<org.springframework.security.core.GrantedAuthority> resolveGrantedAuthorities(Group group)
        Description copied from interface: GroupGrantedAuthorityResolver
        Returns a set of GrantedAuthoritys assigned to a particular Stormpath Group.

        Spring Security checks these granted authorities to determine whether or not an Authentication associated with the Group is permitted to do something.

        Specified by:
        resolveGrantedAuthorities in interface GroupGrantedAuthorityResolver
        Parameters:
        group - the Stormpath Group to inspect to return its assigned Spring Security granted authorities.
        Returns:
        a set of Spring Security GrantedAuthoritys assigned to the group, to be used by Spring Security for runtime authorization checks.
